The overhead lights buzz in Training Room B, a couple dozen folding chairs and maybe half of them filled. FACILITATOR stands at the front, thirties, blazer, a clicker in one hand, smiling out like she's glad every one of them showed up.

FACILITATOR:
Okay. Good turnout for a Thursday, I appreciate it. We're doing Module Seven today, and if you got your name on the sheet by the door then you and I are all set.

She thumbs the clicker.

ON THE SCREEN -- a stylized MAO PORTRAIT hangs above the year 1966, and the words A BOLD QUESTION, WHAT DO WE OWE THE PAST.

FACILITATOR:
This one's honestly one of my favorites. It's an early framework, real early, but there's a lot in here that still holds up if you actually sit with it a minute.

In the third row MACK, fifties, a work shirt and a stub of pencil, opens a pocket notebook flat on his knee.

FACILITATOR:
The whole idea is you take an honest look at what you've been carrying around that maybe you don't need to be carrying anymore.

She clicks again.

ON THE SCREEN -- clean sans-serif on harmony blue, the words OLD IDEAS. OLD CULTURE. OLD CUSTOMS. OLD HABITS.

Mack prints the four words down the page in block letters, one under the other.

BAY TWO MAN, sixties, machinist's forearms, a VISITOR sticker curling on his shirt, lifts a hand a few inches off his knee.

BAY TWO MAN:
Can I ask you. The four up there. What counts as one. An old custom, say, what are we talking about with that.

FACILITATOR:
Oh, great question. So, examples. A handshake deal's a good one, where nobody ever wrote up a real contract, you just shook on it and that was that. That's a custom.

FACILITATOR:
Or, you know, recipes. The kind nobody ever wrote down anywhere, it's just up in somebody's head. That one's more of a habit, or a custom, they kind of blur together, it's fine.

FACILITATOR:
Taking your hat off when a parade goes by, something like that. It all lives in there.

FACILITATOR:
And that's really the beauty of it. Nobody has to hand you a list. You already know what yours are. Every person in this room gets to decide for themselves what counts as old for them, and that's exactly what the reflection piece is going to walk you through.

Nobody in the room makes a sound.

Bay Two Man lowers his hand back to his knee and looks at the floor.

FACILITATOR:
See, I love this. You can feel everybody kind of going inward with it. That's the work happening.

Near the back JOSS, twenties, a bag of sunflower seeds balled in his fist, cracks one against his teeth without raising a hand.

JOSS:
What happened to the people who liked the old stuff?

The clicker goes still in her hand for a second.

FACILITATOR:
So there were — implementation errors, in that era. Which is why the frameworks now, they really center on dialogue.

Joss spits the shell into the bag and cracks another one.

The door swings and PELL leans in, fifties, a federal lanyard and a paper coffee cup, the compliance man working his rounds.

PELL:
Don't mind me. This is the good work, folks. Centuries of ancient Chinese wisdom in that slide.

FACILITATOR:
It's from 1966—

PELL:
Wonderful.

He finds a chair against the back wall and sits down with his coffee, staying.

Facilitator clicks to the last slide.

ON THE SCREEN -- YOUR REFLECTION HOMEWORK, IDENTIFY ONE OLD HABIT YOU'RE READY TO RETIRE!

FACILITATOR:
So that's your one thing for me before next week. Just the one old habit you feel ready to retire. Bring it in and we'll talk it through as a group.

By the door a CLIPBOARD hangs on a short chain, a sign-out sheet clamped under the clip, a pen tied on with a length of string.

Chairs scrape back and the men line up to sign the sheet one at a time.

IN THE CORRIDOR -- Joss falls into step beside Mack, the two of them drifting toward the elevators.

JOSS (WHISPER):
My grandpa's old habit was getting shot at over Hanoi.

MACK:
Write coffee. Everybody writes coffee.
